<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="About The Skeptical Trader — what this site is and why it exists."
>
  <div class="about-body">
    <h1>About</h1>

    <p>
      The Skeptical Trader exists because most financial commentary is optimized for engagement,
      not clarity. Headlines are written to provoke. Analysts have incentives to maintain access.
      Pundits are rewarded for confident predictions, not accurate ones.
    </p>

    <p>
      This site tries to do something different: look at what the data actually says, acknowledge
      what we don't know, and avoid the kind of confident storytelling that makes markets seem
      more predictable than they are.
    </p>

    <p>
      The focus is on macro — monetary policy, fixed income, earnings, economic indicators —
      approached with some skepticism toward both the conventional wisdom and the contrarian
      takes that exist mainly to oppose it. Getting it right matters more than having a position.
    </p>

    <p>
      Articles here are written from the perspective of a long-term observer of markets who has
      learned, mostly through being wrong, that the playbook changes. What worked last cycle may
      not work this one. Indicators that predicted recessions for forty years may stop predicting
      them. The honest response to that is to hold views more loosely, not to pick a new
      certainty and defend it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Nothing on this site is investment advice. If you're making financial decisions based on
      what you read here, please talk to a qualified financial advisor first.
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
